PUSH Operation (Stack)
1. What is Push
Imagine a stack of plates in a hotel.

Top
 ↓
Plate 2
Plate 1

A waiter brings a new plate.

Where will he place it?

Only on the TOP.

He cannot place it in the middle or at the bottom.

This operation is called PUSH.

Definition:

Push is the operation of adding (inserting) a new element onto the top of the stack.

Since a stack follows LIFO (Last In, First Out), every new element is always placed on the top.

2. Syntax in Java
stack.push(element);

Example

Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

stack.push(10);
stack.push(20);
stack.push(30);
3. Visualization

Initially

Empty Stack

Top
 ↓
-----
Push(10)
stack.push(10);
Top
 ↓
10
Push(20)
stack.push(20);
Top
 ↓
20
10
Push(30)
stack.push(30);
Top
 ↓
30
20
10

Notice:

Every new element is added above the previous top element.

4. Step-by-Step Working

Suppose the stack is

Top
 ↓
20
10

Now execute

stack.push(30);
Step 1

Create the new element

30
Step 2

Place it above the current top

Top
 ↓
30
20
10
Step 3

Update the Top pointer

Now 30 becomes the new Top.

5. Example Program
import java.util.Stack;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

        stack.push(10);
        stack.push(20);
        stack.push(30);

        System.out.println(stack);
    }
}
Output
[10, 20, 30]

Note:

Java prints the stack from bottom to top.

So

[10, 20, 30]

means

Top
 ↓
30
20
10
6. What Does push() Return?

Many beginners think push() returns nothing.

Actually,

push() returns the element that was inserted.

Example

Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();

int x = stack.push(50);

System.out.println(x);

Output

50

Although in most programs we simply write

stack.push(50);

without storing the returned value.

7. Time Complexity
Operation	Time Complexity
Push	O(1)
Why?

Because the new element is always added at the top.

No searching.

No shifting.

No traversal.

Only one insertion.

Therefore,

Time Complexity = O(1)

8. What Happens Internally?

Suppose

Index

0   1
-------
10  20

top = 1

Now

push(30)

Internally

top = top + 1

stack[top] = 30

Now

Index

0   1   2
-----------
10  20  30

top = 2

The Top pointer moves one position upward.

9. Push in Array Implementation

Initially

Index

0   1   2   3   4
------------------
10  20

top = 1

Push

top = top + 1

stack[top] = 30

Final

Index

0   1   2   3   4
------------------
10  20  30

top = 2
10. Push in Linked List Implementation

Initially

Head (Top)

↓

20 → 10 → null

Push(30)

Create a new node

30

Make it point to the old head

newNode.next = head;

Update head

head = newNode;

Final Stack

Head (Top)

↓

30 → 20 → 10 → null

The new node becomes the Top.

11. Overflow

What if the stack is already full?

Suppose the stack size is 5

Top
 ↓
50
40
30
20
10

Now

push(60);

There is no space.

This situation is called

Stack Overflow

For an array implementation, you should check

if(top == capacity - 1)
{
    System.out.println("Stack Overflow");
}

Note:

Java's built-in Stack grows dynamically, so you usually won't encounter overflow with java.util.Stack.

12. Safe Way (Array Implementation)

Before pushing

if(top < capacity - 1)
{
    push(element);
}
else
{
    System.out.println("Stack Overflow");
}
